American wild/sour ale brewed with apricots, dry hopped with El Dorado, Columbus, and Cascade, and conditioned on oak.  Crush crush crush.

2015 GABF gold medal and 2014 GABF silver medal in the imperial stout category.  Double Negative pours jet black with burnt orange highlights.  A long lasting tan head leaves abundant lacing. Aromas bursting from the glass include espresso, bitter chocolate, caramel, black currant and blueberry.  Creamy and viscous on the palate, the flavor initially follows the nose.  A pop of smooth bitterness comes after, and then a lingering, roasty finish.

Super Spruce owes its immense pine aromatics to a double dose of resin. The new growth of spruce trees layered with Chinook hops create a complex profile of fresh pine that includes floral, citrus, cola, and bubble gum undertones. This unboiled beer is luminous and hazy with a grapefruit-like acidity that perfectly showcases the bright coniferous flavors. Sea salt rounds the mouthfeel, while white oak provides tannic structure.

Beautifully hazed-up new school IPA.  Juicy and soft with an aroma that catches your attention from across the room.  Velvety mouthfeel, soft bitterness.  Citra, Mosaic, Equinox, and El Dorado varietals kicking out a range of tropical flavors.  Perfectly balanced and dialed in.  Draft only.  Born on 1/11/16.

Hazy and richly aromatic. Aggressively dry hopped with new German aroma hops Mandarina Bavaria and Huell Melon; orange zest to boot. Lightly toasted white oak provides tannins and mouthfeel. Assertively tart, with light sea salt appearing on the finish. Citrus and hop flavors galore. Absolutely mouthwatering.
Single IPA brewed with oats, featuring Rakau hops against background elements of Citra, Mosaic, and Columbus.
Blackcurrants, raspberries, aged hops, new oak.  Juicy, tart, tannic, delicious.
Brewed with blackberries and blueberries, conditioned on oak, and dry hopped with hüll Melon.
Refreshing, crushable dry hopped sour ale featuring hops from Germany and New Zealand (Huell Melon, Hallertau Blanc, Southern Cross) and conditioned on white oak.

Telekinesis is a hoppy, tart, and smashable American wild ale fermented with a mixed culture of yeast and spontaneous microbes. Mosaic, Citra, and Falconer’s Flight hops contribute peachy, tropical hop character. Lightly toasted white oak spirals lend subtle tannin structure, while our no-boil process leaves a puckering hint of raw sourdough.

This American red sour ale balances a juicy acidity against a backdrop of malty sweetness.  Conditioned in stainless tanks with oak spirals and tart Montmorency cherries, this is a shamelessly unfaithful tribute to the red-brown beers of Flanders we love so much.  Lightly toasted bread on the nose, sweet and tart on the palate, with a touch of cherry on the long, complex finish.

Reigning GABF gold medal imperial stout Double Negative has taken home hardware two years straight.  This is that base beer, with ultra dark maple syrup added, aged in heaven hill bourbon barrels.

A more delicate, sessionable take on a Grimm IPA brewed with El Dorado and Columbus hops. Inviting hop aromas of cotton candy, honeysuckle, tangerine, watermelon. Crisp and dry, highly drinkable with moderate bitterness. Finishes clean and refreshing.

A tart, double-dry-hopped wild ale with a big tropical nose of El Dorado, Columbus, and Falconer’s Flight hops. Several strains of lacto, wild yeasts, and The Yeast Formerly Known As Brett Trois. Grapefruit pith and mango notes, backed by a balanced earthy funk. Hazy crusher. Draft only.

beers.beerDescription: Original Sin is a critically acclaimed cider launched in 1997. From day one we’ve been committed to producing premium quality cider using the finest ingredients. Original Sin contains no artificial flavors or colors allowing the natural qualities of the apple to speak for itself.

Elderberry is a common fruit used in wine making. Its unique tart qualities make it an ideal fruit to use in the cider making process. Much of making a good cider is finding the perfect balance between acid, sugar and tannins. With Original Sin Elderberry, the Company believes it has achieved this balance. There is a long history of Elderberries being used in cider production. In fact, in the 1822 book ‘The American Orchardist’, it suggests adding Elderberries to give “cider a fine colour as well as flavor.”

Fresh Pressed Heirloom Apples Combined with Tart U.S. Cherries.

Our Cherry Tree cider combines the finest American heirloom apples, which were popular in the United States in the 18th and 19th centuries, with tart cherries. The finished product has the clean, rich flavor of fresh cherries with the depth and elegance that comes from using freshly pressed U.S. heirloom cider apples.

Original Sin Pear Cider was developed in line with the company’s mission to produce traditional cider leaving out artificial flavors and additives. Original Sin Pear is light and refreshing with a clean, dry finish.

reviews.text: Bronx Brewery hasn’t yet gained the fame and crowds of Brooklyn Brewing, but it seems poised to be the next breakout brewery. The setting is good for hanging out most of the day and it helps that the beer is pretty good. They do not serve food so bring something and make a picnic. They have about a dozen brews on tap of various styles and strength. The flagship Banner Ale and the Octoberfest were two of my favorites. They are even dog friendly at the outside section which is awesome. The outside is pretty big with a bunch of picnic tables while inside only has seating for a few folks. The only odd part is the layout where you have to walk through the brewery to get to the outside which can be a bit of a pain with a dog and stroller (if so inclined). It’s a good place to bring some food and hang out for the whole day while sampling their full range. It does get a bit crowded on weekend evenings these days.
Nice selection I  a tiny space. Snacks offered,  no hot food. Lots of IPA selections. No select parking lot for the space. Fun spot.
I went for a tour and tasting.  Well mostly for the tasting.  It was different to see different people in an area of the Bronx that was not so nice a short time ago.   The bartender was great.

Finally made it to this brewery, I have had a lot of Bronx Brewery American Pale Ales at different event and bars around New York City. It is great to see this destination brewery with my own eyes. Now, this area is an industrial location in the South Bronx.  Driving would be the best way to get here but our group of three decided to take the subway which is very doable with a ten minute walk from the 6 Train stop.

As you approach and enter this large industrial facility, there is tasting room to the left and straight ahead to go into the brewery. If you go through the brewery area, there is a large outdoor space. It's December now so it is definitely off-season for this outdoor location but I was told by the Brooklyn Brewery staff and tour guide, Kate that it is a great space on a summer weekend. They are food trucks and live music. I definitely need to come back and check it out.

They offer free tours of the brewery on the weekend. It was a quiet Sunday afternoon so we had a private tour because we were the only new arrivals at tour time. Kate explained very succinctly and efficiently the brewing process and more about Bronx Brewery. Bronx Brewery stated in 2011 but it only opened this brewery location in 2014 after a few years of renovation woes, thanks Hurricane Sandy.

If you check-in with Yelp, you get $1 off a pint after your tasting. We took advantage of this discount which was much appreciated. We decided to eat before we arrived but there is a good selection of small appetizer types of food such as prosciutto ($10), pretzels ($6) and toketti ($6). The toketti are Sardinian style flatbread chip-type munchies.

For the beer, we tried plenty of brews. We ended up with three different pints. The Rye Pale Ale was our first selection a crisp, golden-orange pale ale with rye and piney hops.  The other two selections were the seasonal brews, Winter and Bogsmash. The Winter Pale Ale is an amber colored pale ale brewed with cinnamon, molasses, cloves and ginger that has a spiced the flavor.  The Bogsmash Pale Ale is a fall brew with cranberries with a subtle tart aftertaste.

A few of my friends have personally recommended this location so I am happy to have made it to this location.

The Bronx Brewery is a great place to hang out with friends, drink a mellow local brew, and grab a bite to eat at the food truck in the back.  The summer ale is very delicious and just-right for the hot summer.  Once you get a beer, head to the outdoor seating area and listen to the live music on weekends.  Good for meeting friends and small groups.
My company had a work event here and it was tons of fun. They had tons of cans in ice tubs laying around. They had their two backyard taps open with beers I...

beers.beerDescription: This deep amber American-style pale ale is brewed with 5 different barley malts, generous additions of Cascade and Centennial hops, and a unique strain of yeast. It is dry-hopped, unfiltered, and unpasteurized.

Malted and flaked rye make up nearly a quarter of the grain bill for this Rye Pale Ale, offering it a unique and intense spicy rye flavor and golden-orange hue.  Chinook and Crystal hops lend a gentle bitterness and spicy, piney and herbal character and aroma to this rich, bold rye beer.

This balanced and refreshing pale ale is perfect for summer days in the city.  Brewed with British and American 2-row malts, a unique experimental hop variety and dried lemon peel, it offers a subtle and crisp citrus note.  It is dry-hopped, unfiltered and unpasteurized.

Loads of tropical fruit – guava, passion fruit and ripe mango – on the nose, a clean, light body, leading to a refreshingly tart, red wheat malt finish establish this easy-drinking yet wonderfully hoppy 5.0% ABV session IPA.

Two strains of Trappist yeast, one Belgian ale yeast, and Belgian candi sugar highlight this remarkably intricate, fruity, spicy, and earthy straw-colored Belgian Pale Ale. Belgian Pilsner and Biscuit malts from Beloeil and German Vienna malts from Bamberg provide a clean backdrop for the spicy and lightly herbal Sterling hops. A votre santé from the Bronx.

This Black Pale Ale offers a smooth and complex contrast of dark chocolate and roasted malt flavors with bright and tropical guava, mango and pear hop flavors and aromas.  Three different American malts stand up to generous amounts of West Coast El Dorado and Citra hops in an unfiltered and unpasteurized ale.  Embrace the darkness of the winter with this hoppy black ale.

If you are looking for a beer to satisfy your New Year's resolution, make no mistake -- this isn't it. This brew brings hop aromas & bitterness in a big way -- a variety of hops create a spectrum of aromas ranging from citrus, pine, musky, tropical fruit to lemon grass. With a 7.6% ABV and a heavy hop guarantee this is the ideal beer for those who go No Resolutions. Cheers!

Our banner beer for those who make stuff happen.

Bronx Banner is a Kolsch-inspired ale that is brewed using Belgian pilsner, American wheat malts & classic Bavarian hops.  It’s brilliantly clear-filtered, soft and perfectly balanced.
An amber colored pale ale brewed with cinnamon, molasses, cloves & ginger that delivers a delightful winter spiced flavor.

Fresh juice pressed from New York State apples makes up a quarter of the fermentables of this crisp and easy-drinking Autumn Pale Ale, lending it a slightly acidic, fruity and tannic finish.  Northern Brewer hops from the west coast are added to the kettle and conditioning tank, contributing a woody and subtle mint character.

beers.beerName: Bronx Spring Pale Ale with Tea
beers.beerDescription: A blend of black and chamomile teas brewed to perfect balance with 2 row barley malts and refreshing lemongrass and pine hop bitterness.

A fall seasonal brewed with cranberries giving this pale ale a subtle tart finish.

Cranberries can only grow in a few parts of the world and lucky for us, NY State happens to be one of them.  We used cranberries from a few of NY's best bogs to add a subtle tartness to this seasonal pale ale.  The hops we use provide woody aromas & bitterness and the malt's sweetness keeps the acidity of the berries in check.  We feel the Bog Smash is the perfect complement for the crisp outdoor weather we love to enjoy in the fall.  Plus, it's super fun to yell "Bog Smash", so hope you enjoy!

Big floral and tropical aromas set up this delightfully balanced white IPA.

Soft yet slightly tart wheat and lightly toasted malts are complemented by the gentle bitterness of the hops.  Our brewers use late hop additions and dry hopping in the brewing process to give this IPA its big hop nose without an overwhelmingly bitter taste.  This brew is love at first smell.  Cheers!

A rich, full bodied stout that delivers a dark roasted and chocolate taste that would make any coffee drinker smile.

Heaps of small-batch roasted Ethiopian coffee from Uptown Coffee Roasters (our next door neighbor) lead the charge in this rich, creamy coffee milk stout.  The milk sugar we add gives it plenty of sweetness but it’s balanced by floral, earthy and mildly bitter Willamette hops so you won’t have too much sugar in your coffee.  If you’re looking for something sweet and chocolatey to warm you up on a cold NYC winter night look no further.

Easy drinking IPA with loads of tropical hops & subtle tart finish.
To keep pace in New York City you've got to be able to get things done in a New York minute.  It's a fast-paced, frenzied lifestyle that we love being part of but now and then it's good to pump the brakes a bit and slow it all down.  This Session IPA is perfect for those chill moments when you want to lean back and take it all in. We brew this IPA with two of our favorite hops for some amazing tropical fruit aromas and add red wheat malt to give it a crisp, tart finish.  An easy drinking 4.6% ABV makes this the ideal brew for when it's time to Slow Your Roll.

A spicy Rye IPA that’s balanced with a generous amount of West Coast hops, giving this brew a strong, pleasant bitterness and raising it to Imperial status with an 8.1% ABV. Our devotion to our Rye Ale runs deep.  After all, it was the second beer we ever brewed.  But we couldn’t resist the temptation to make a bigger, more badass version and this spicy Rye IPA delivers.  With heavy citrus aromas on thenose and a crisp, dry, warm finish on the mouth, it’s a complex, yet finely balanced big hoppy beer with an 8.1% ABV that we can’t get enough of.  Looks like we committed some infidelity with our Rye Fidelity.

We figured we'd kick off our Bronx Barrel Reserve series with a bang, by short aging our White IPA in NY State red wine barells. The mix of different wine varietals lends notes to strawberries, raspberries, and plums to our already massively juicy IPA.  While resting in these wine barrels we add a dry hop of Pacific Gem and Citra to help set this beer off like a firework for your senses.
A big, fun Red IPA that brings all the spice & heat without the burn!

A refreshingly spicy farmhouse style saison right in time for the summer.

The origins of saison were grounded in the use of this brew by many farmers in Belgium and France as a form of payment (and sustenance) to their farmhands during the hot summer months.  While we here at The Bronx Brewery prefer modern forms of currency, our Brewmaster thought this would be a nice little bonus for the summer.  A complex, yet refreshingly easy to drink beer.  We added 60 pounds of orange blossom honey into the kettle to give this farmhouse ale a delightful citric & sweet aroma.  The malts deliver an earthy and malty biscuit sweetness and the Austrian and Czech hops balance it all with spicy, herbal flavor and aromatic.
Double IPA, brewed with tangerine purée

A crisp & easy drinking pale ale brewed with freshly pressed apple juice.

This pale ale is made using freshly pressed juice from apples from Soons Orchard in upstate New York.  The apples provide a dry and slight fruity taste balanced by Northern Brewer hops for a subtle wood and mint character. beers.beerName: Red Zinfandel Aged American Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: This deep amber, American-style pale ale is brewed with five different barley malts, generous additions of Cascade and Centennial hops, and a unique strain of yeast. American hefeweizen yeast imparts classic wheat beer characteristics and dry hopping will deliver a heavy dose of hops on the nose.  There’s no doubt this beer is a hit.

beers.beerDescription: The hop profile of Flagship APA includes an upfront bitterness complemented with citrus and pine-like aromas followed by a small burst of tropical fruit. Malted barley provides a deep auburn color and a sweet, biscuit-like backbone helping the flavor balance nicely with the bitterness from the hops. The mouthfeel is medium bodied with a hoppy and crisp finish.

Flagship American Wit is a refreshing, light bodied wheat beer. Prized hops from America’s northwest region give this ale a citrusy flavor blended with the subtle undertones of our hand ground spices. A balancing malt profile contributes a recognizable golden color in addition to a slight haze from the yeast.

Flagship Brewery’s “Metropolitan Lager” is a golden lager that features toasted Vienna and Rye malts. The Rye adds a smooth mouthfeel while floral noble hops are used in abundance for flavor and aroma. This lager is smooth, clean, crisp and exceptionally balanced.

A showcase of some of Flagship’s favorite hop varieties and executed by using them in abundance. Each hop in IPA lends a unique flavor that when blended produces bursting fruit flavors from citrusy grapefruit to tropical mango in harmony with an ever so slight roast character from the golden malted barley. Designed for full hop flavor experience without overpowering bitterness.

A malty brew that uses Vienna and Munich varieties of malted barley that are complemented with German malted rye and German chocolate rye. Bavarian noble hops balance the beer with a mild bitterness and soft floral aroma. The result is a full-bodied dark copper colored ale with a smooth texture and spicy-like characteristic from the rye malt.

Flagship Dark Mild is black in color due to a complex malt profile that’s packed with flavor by using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts. The mildness comes from a soft hop character and lower alcohol content making this light bodied ale a sessionable salute to our fondness for dark beer.

A foundation consisting of American wheat and Golden Promise malts give this beer light sweetness and a slight haze. The all-star of this ale is a hop called “Summer.” This spawn of the noble hop, Saaz, is subtle and used in abundance contributing slight aromas of hop spice, earthiness, and tropical melon. American ale yeast helps to provide a crispness that is dry but balanced. Deep yellow color and a light body make this summer beer approachable and sessionable.

As we approach the inevitable winter, Flagship introduces “Wee Heavy.”  Brewed in the style of strong Scottish ales, a longer boil adds “caramelization” to the brewing process and helps produce a full body and higher alcohol content in addition to malty sweetness. We Americanize this dark brown colored beer by using a copious amount of pacific northwest hops.

The British Mild is a session ale known for soft hop character and lower alcohol content. Flagship VAN DAM is black in color due to a complex malt profile. Using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts, this ale is bursting with dark beer character. The addition of Madagascar Bourbon vanilla blends a pleasant richness to the existing flavors. A medium but mellow body gives VAN DAM enjoyable drinkability during the winter months.

The pairing of Stout with oysters has been enjoyed for centuries and Flagship Oyster Stout combines the two into one delicious apéritif. Roasted barley united with chocolate rye, midnight wheat, and flaked oats gives this brew dark color and roasty flavor while providing a smooth mouthfeel and rich body. The flavor blends nicely with a mineral brininess from Long Island harvested oysters that are boiled in the brewing process, shell and all. Designed to be enjoyed with oysters raw or cooked, but approachable and encouraged to be enjoyed all occasions.

In 1642, the first Dutch Colonists came to Queens (present day Maspeth). But within that first year, they got their asses kicked, then booted out (back to Manhattan Island) by the Mespeatches Native American tribe (origins of the name 'Maspeth'). This beer is a recipe using ingredients that those first Dutch colonists would have had access to in 1642. Barley and Cluster hops were available at the time but often in short supply, so to supplement a recipe, colonial brewers used corn, rye, wheat, oats, buckwheat, and honey in their grain bills. To supplement bittering hops if in short supply, spruce tips would be used. All above ingredies are included in this recipe. The rsult is a balanced, sessiony ale - slightly cloudy (from the wheat), slightly earthy and bitter (from the spruce addition) - with a story to ponder... Sort of the 'b' side version of the story of Thanksgiving. 
Call it a colonial pale, old fashioned ale, a gruit, or whatever category you think fits.

reviews.text: The beers are pretty solid, but none are really my cup of tea. Then again I like specific types of beer and don't necessarily appreciate every style, so it could just be me. The taproom is pretty bare bones. It is cool looking but very hot and humid. You couldn't put your bag or anything on the floor, for example. You could bring your dog in though. It is usually a little lively but not crowded. The staff is nice always. I have purchased their to-go beers multiple times, and I do like the Empire State signature cans. Again, all around solid, and depending on your beer tastes, maybe stellar.
Friendly staff. Great place to have a flight (4oz for 7) or two. Some of the beers were pretty tasty. Good small spot in the back for a quick brewery tour if you have never done before.

Pretty great beer, nice to have in a neighborhood like this!  The taproom is a bit smaller than I expected, so it may be a bit difficult to get a seat in the busier times, but it's a great brewery to visit.
If it's your first time, try one of the flights! Good beer. Fun atmosphere. Nice staff.

reviews.text: Cool little place. Clean, nice layout for warmer weather (open garage style). Would be great if they had some bar snacks to pair with their beers.
Really like this spot. Great beers and a nice wide-open feel to the brewery makes it a perfect location for drinks with the crew. I think Higher Burnin' is one of the best beers I've ever had.
We enjoyed sampling the different beers here, especially the sour. Nice environment although its not overly large, staff was friendly and helpful.
Friendly staff, great rotating selection of fabulous Belgian style beers and the most relaxed atmosphere for a brewery in the area.
The beer ranges from decent to fantastic. The service, at its best, is only a notch above ambivalent. I will not return; however, I will happily order their beer at other venues.

beers.beerDescription: Our newest India Pale Ale brewed with late additions of Belma, El Dorado, and Mosaic resulting in a medium bodied IPA with juicy fruit, strawberry, earthy and piney notes finishing resinous and dry.

A Belgian inspired golden ale brewed with our house saison yeast and generously hopped with a blend of aromatic noble hops. The final result is softly contoured pale golden ale with an aroma rife with floral, spice and earth. The finish is crisp and dry.

Pile of Crowns is a medium bodied Imperial IPA, which employs a blend of hops including Citra, Mosaic, and Nugget. This exceedingly aromatic ale entices with peach, mango, and papaya. It finishes smooth and dry with accents of orange and berries.

India pale ale brewed with a blend of American and British 2-row, wheat, oats, crystal and double dry hopped with Citra, Simcoe, and Columbus.  Pine, resin, passionfruit, grapefruit, and orange with hints of melon.
Hoppy Brett Ale

SAMO (pronounced SAY-MO) features the remarkable complexities of American hops: Cascade, Centennial, Citra, and Simcoe.  Hazy and pale orange in appearance, SAMO erupts with citrus, mango, and dank pine aromatics. Bold, juicy flavors of tropical fruit, peach and cantaloupe.  Finishes bone dry yet soft and creamy.

A kolsch-inspired ale named after LICBP's neighborhood.This golden ale is brewed with a Kolsch yeast and has a gentle malt forward flavor.  In the aroma there are hints of pear and floral notes from the German Hallertau Mittelfrüh hops.  Very traditional in style, this beer was lagered to achieve a bright and clean finish.

Party Crasher is an easy drinking IPA loaded with late addition Citra and Mosaic hops.  The aroma is fruit citrus with an earthy pine resin.  A subtle hop bitterness leads to a soft malt backbone.  The beer finishes long and dry.

Brewed in collaboration with Root + Branch Brewing. Brewed with American malted barley, wheat malt and flaked oats. Hopped with a blend of
American citrus forward hops. Fermented with our house ale yeast strain.
Double dry hopped. Features prominent notes of grapefruit and candied orange
with undertones of stone fruit and sticky pine. 42 IBU / 5.5% ABV
Rye Saison

A French country ale brewed with our house saison yeast. Appearance is a deep leathery copper with a pillowy beige head. Big spice and bready malt character on the palate from the generous additions of Munich malt, Special B, and orange peel. Lagered cold, this beer finishes clean and dry with a firm earthy bitterness.

This decidedly American take on a Belgian saison is expressing ripe aromatics that blur the line between hops and yeast. A well hopped saison with grassy floral notes, hints of bubblegum, and bready malt. Finishes light body with a noticeable bitterness.
Double IPA hopped with late addition Galaxy, Mosaic, Belma, and Columbus.
Belgian style singel ale brewed with generous late additions of Saaz and Amarillo hops. Fermented with a Trappist ale yeast strain.
Conditioned on lemons, limes, and oranges.
This Imperial Stout was brewed with Blackstrap molasses then conditioned on cocoa nibs, Birch cold brew coffee, Vietnamese cinnamon, vanilla beans, and cascabel peppers.

reviews.text:
As an out of town guest, second timer...Fun atmosphere! Always changing decor. Cool vibe. Great beer selection. Good music. 

Negative... 2nd time here, 
short female bartender, zero personality sadly, seems not friendly at all. Its like you're bothering her for walking up to the counter. #rude. 😝

Positive... all other workers seem really nice. One guy in particular super cool, helped me both visits at bar, African American guy, stocky 💪, great, positive attitude... I own a small business where customer service is key...  he's a great addition!

I'm really disappointed. I was excited to finally visit this place whilst in town, but the whole experience was unpleasant. They seem to want to run the place like a crappy nightclub or something--they're completely missing when it comes to catering to the general type of audience that visits breweries.

First, this place was somewhat difficult to locate. When we finally found it, the door was wide open and we walked in. Some disgruntled bouncer sort asked us what we were doing and why we just walked in. We informed him that the door was wide open and there was no one outside. So, he made us go stand in line? Why? Who knows, probably for the sake of being pretentious. Then, while we're standing there, the two bouncer guys are making snide comments about women walking by. Come on, guys, how sleazy can you get? When they finally decided to let us in, it was stand in line for tokens then stand in line for beers. All of the people working in the place had bad attitudes and were quite rude or just generally impolite. The place was very crowded but not unlike other breweries I've seen; the problem was that you couldn't talk to anyone because the crappy music they were playing was so loud. My friend and I finished up our two beers and got out of there quick.

In a word: unpleasant. In another word: sleazy.
It was definitely not the typical brewery experience. Go once, try your best to enjoy it, then don't go back.

What can I say? Fantastic beers, place gets super-full and noisy, but you can still talk if you wander away from the bar over to where the brewing tanks are. Simple Pleasures: East IPA, straight from the tap at the brewery - delicious and refreshing. Also the Local 1 Belgian-style Golden Ale (which is almost too easy to drink, considering its whopping 9% alcohol content)

The beer is great. Good staples as choices and the quality and freshness was what you'd expect. Staff was friendly and quick. 

The big downside is the setup of this place: you wait in a line to get in, then wait in a line to get tokens, then wait in a line to exchange those tokens for beer. Could they have a more convoluted process? The tables and seating might as well not exist as the place is over-crowded and, as other reviewers note, full of drunk twenty-somethings. 

Bottom line: If you're a grumpy old person - prepare to be unhappy. If you're a drunk twenty-something - prepare to wait in line to get decent beer surrounded by your peers and frowning old(er) people.

We came in on the first warm Saturday of the year, around 4pm, which was way too late. The line was crazy long, and they sold out of tour tickets for the rest of the day, and the line to get tokens was too long and the line to get beer was long and... I don't know. I just didn't love it. 

Pros: Very cool space. 
Cons: It was overcrowded. And $5 for a plastic cup of beer is fine, I guess, but I wish they'd had more sample options (tastings of all the beers for like $20 or something).

We ended up talking our way onto the 4:30 tour by chance, which redeemed this trip - but I wouldn't count on that working again. The tour was pretty simple, the tour guide was cool and funny but it was pretty basic. Not sure I'd come back, honestly, or recommend it to anyone if they're not super into Brooklyn Brewery already.

We were on the pursuit of hoppiness and we found it here! :D

This place is pretty cool. It's big and spacious but it's hard to find seats. The line moves...

Brooklyn Pennant Ale is a honey-colored pale ale with a brisk malt palate and finely balanced hop character. Pennant is a traditional English-style pale ale. Ours is brewed from Scottish Maris Otter malt, which is justly prized for its toasty, biscuity flavor and the round smoothness it imparts to beer. Our house ale yeast brings out an appetizing fruitiness and ferments to a dry finish.

Here in New York City, things are complicated, fast and loud. So sometimes we want a nice beer that's simply tasty and refreshing. Brooklyn American Ale is easygoing, versatile, and dependable. It's a beer you and your friends can hang out with, no matter where you're from. Try it alongside pizza, burgers, spicy foods, sharp cheese, or just another bottle of American Ale.
Traditional dry stout with flavors of milk chocolate and coffee.

Brooklyn Scorcher IPA is a surprisingly sessionable IPA. A floral, piney aroma strikes first, followed by a burst of mouthwatering bitterness as the hops begin their attack. Suddenly, a hint of toasty malt and a clean, lively finish burst in to leave you thirsty for more. It’s ludicrously tasty, and at a reasonable 4.5%, it’s a beer you can come back to again and again. Try it with spicy foods, salads, grilled meats, cheddar, feta or just another Scorcher IPA.
Layers of rich roasted malts bundled up in a smooth dark lager.
Intense russian imperial stout aged in bourbon barrels and 100% bottle refermented.
Bottle refermented belgian-inspired dark abbey ale with dark fruit flavors and complex aroma.

The Defender is constantly vigilant, standing guard over all those who dare to create, to dream, and to drink great beer. This bright, juicy, West Coast-style IPA takes on a reddish twist from a dash of roasted malt. Bold, fruity hop bitterness and an intensely resinous nose lead the way into a dry finish that blazes the trail for your next sip. Brooklyn Defender IPA was forged in collaboration with our sidekicks at New York Comic Con as the official beer of the convention.

We've been friends with Danny Meyer and the team behind Shake Shack since their early days at the Union Square Cafe. In 2008, shortly before the expansion that would bring their Madison Square Park Shake Shack to the world stage, they came to us and asked if we could create a beer to match their delicious burgers. A job like that would call for a great deal of burger-related research, so we jumped at the opportunity.

A great many "field trial burgers" later, we delivered the first kegs of Brooklyn Shackmeister Ale to Madison Square Park. Today, Shacks around the world proudly stock the nobly-purposed ale. We brew Shackmeister Ale as a hearty pale ale with plenty of malts to match the rich, griddled beef in every Shackburger. A bright burst of hops unifies the finish and invites the drinker to take another bite and accompanying sip.
Wheat beer produced in cooperation with GrowNYC using 70% NYS grain.
Delightfully fruity and tart dry-hopped sour ale.

Brooklyn Intensified Coffee Porter starts as a big, chocolatey ale, ready to take on super powers. The first power is gained from months of aging in Kentucky bourbon barrels. The second arises from delectable beans harvested by our pals at Finca El Manzano Single Origin Coffee in El Salvador. The final power comes from Blue Bottle Coffee, who roast the coffee to perfection. Brace yourself for complex notes of dark chocolate, vanilla, oak, berries, and dried fruit, coming to intensify you.
